  "proof_sketch": "The missing __syncthreads() after the max reduction loop causes a race condition where threads from other warps may read a stale value of shared_max[0] before thread 0's final write becomes visible. This race requires specific timing and is non-deterministic. The previous attempt used a single large value at index 255 but only ran once, so the race likely did not occur. Our strategy uses a pattern that maximizes the difference between the true max and the stale max (even indices very negative, odd indices moderate) and runs the kernel many times to increase the probability of the race manifesting.",
  "survival_reason": "The mutation removes a __syncthreads() after the max reduction loop. Without it, threads in warps other than the one containing thread 0 may read an intermediate max value from shared memory before thread 0's final write is globally visible. This race condition is non-deterministic and very sensitive to GPU scheduling, warp alignment, and memory latency. Previous tests with random inputs or single runs failed to trigger the race because they did not maximize the consequent difference or run sufficient repetitions. Our input ensures that the stale max is drastically different from the true max, and repeated execution (e.g., 1000 times) provides enough opportunity for the race to occur.",
  "killable": true,
  "kill_strategy": "Create a tensor where all even-indexed features in each row are set to a very negative value (e.g., -100.0) and all odd-indexed features are set to 1.0. This guarantees that the true max is 1.0 (from odd indices), but the stale max read (max of even indices) is -100.0. Then run the forward pass with the same input many times (e.g., 1000 iterations) and compare each output bitwise against the reference PyTorch softmax. If any iteration produces a different result, the mutant is killed.",
  "suggested_test": {
    "description": "Input where each row has even-index elements = -100.0 and odd-index elements = 1.0. Run the forward pass 1000 times with the same tensor to trigger the race condition caused by missing __syncthreads().",
    "python_code": "def generate_inputs(device):\n    import torch\n    batch_size, num_features = 16, 16384\n    x = torch.full((batch_size, num_features), 1.0, dtype=torch.float32, device=device)\n    x[:, 0::2] = -100.0  # even indices set to -100\n    # Note: 0::2 selects indices 0,2,4,...; we want even indices, that's correct.\n    return [x]"
  },
  "recommendations": "When writing GPU kernels, always include __syncthreads() after any reduction loop to ensure all threads have completed their writes before any thread reads the result, especially when the last iteration only involves a subset of threads. Even if the hardware often makes the write visible, the behavior is undefined without the barrier. To test such races, use repeated execution with inputs that magnify the potential error (e.g., contrast between even and odd indices). This is a classic example of a race that is notoriously difficult to detect with single runs."
}
